# Next.js 16 Server Rendering / Server-Side Primitives

Concise patterns for the App Router, based on the official docs.

## Core Mental Model

In modern Next.js, the main server-side patterns are:

- Server Components by default
- Static rendering by default
- Dynamic rendering for request-time data
- Streaming with `loading.tsx` or `Suspense`
- ISR for static pages that refresh in the background
- Server Actions for forms and mutations
- Cache invalidation with `revalidatePath()` and `revalidateTag()`

## 1. Server And Client Components

Pages and layouts in `app/` are Server Components by default.

Use a Server Component when:

- you fetch data on the server
- you want less client JavaScript
- you do not need browser-only hooks like `useState`

```tsx
// app/posts/page.tsx
export default async function Page() {
	const res = await fetch('https://api.example.com/posts')
	const posts = await res.json()

	return (
		<ul>
			{posts.map((post: { id: string; title: string }) => (
				<li key={post.id}>{post.title}</li>
			))}
		</ul>
	)
}
```

Use `'use client'` only for interactive pieces.

```tsx
'use client'

import { useState } from 'react'

export function Counter() {
	const [count, setCount] = useState(0)

	return <button onClick={() => setCount(count + 1)}>{count}</button>
}
```

## 2. Static Rendering

By default, Next.js tries to cache as much as possible. That means many routes
are statically rendered and reused across requests.

```tsx
// app/blog/page.tsx
export default async function Page() {
	const res = await fetch('https://api.example.com/posts')
	const posts = await res.json()

	return (
		<ul>
			{posts.map((post: { id: string; title: string }) => (
				<li key={post.id}>{post.title}</li>
			))}
		</ul>
	)
}
```

This is server-rendered, but it is not the same as per-request SSR.

## 3. Dynamic Rendering

If you need fresh data on every request, opt out of the route cache.

```tsx
// app/dashboard/page.tsx
async function getProjects() {
	const res = await fetch('https://api.example.com/projects', {
		cache: 'no-store',
	})

	return res.json()
}

export default async function DashboardPage() {
	const projects = await getProjects()

	return (
		<ul>
			{projects.map((project: { id: string; name: string }) => (
				<li key={project.id}>{project.name}</li>
			))}
		</ul>
	)
}
```

This is the App Router version of classic SSR.

A route also becomes dynamic when it uses request-specific data like
`cookies()`, `headers()`, or `searchParams`.

```tsx
// app/account/page.tsx
import { cookies } from 'next/headers'

export default async function AccountPage() {
	const theme = (await cookies()).get('theme')?.value

	return <p>Theme: {theme}</p>
}
```

## 4. Streaming

Streaming lets the user see part of the UI before all data is ready.

### Route-level streaming with `loading.tsx`

```tsx
// app/reports/loading.tsx
export default function Loading() {
	return <p>Loading reports...</p>
}
```

```tsx
// app/reports/page.tsx
export default async function ReportsPage() {
	const res = await fetch('https://api.example.com/reports', {
		cache: 'no-store',
	})
	const reports = await res.json()

	return <pre>{JSON.stringify(reports, null, 2)}</pre>
}
```

### Component-level streaming with `Suspense`

```tsx
// app/analytics/page.tsx
import { Suspense } from 'react'

async function SlowChart() {
	const res = await fetch('https://api.example.com/analytics', {
		cache: 'no-store',
	})
	const data = await res.json()

	return <pre>{JSON.stringify(data, null, 2)}</pre>
}

export default function AnalyticsPage() {
	return (
		<>
			<h1>Analytics</h1>
			<Suspense fallback={<p>Loading chart...</p>}>
				<SlowChart />
			</Suspense>
		</>
	)
}
```

Use `loading.tsx` for the route shell. Use `Suspense` for slower nested parts.

## 5. ISR

ISR means:

- the route is still static
- the result is cached
- after the revalidation window passes, the next request gets stale content
- Next.js regenerates a fresh version in the background
- later requests get the new cached version

### Time-based ISR

```tsx
// app/blog/page.tsx
export const revalidate = 3600

export default async function BlogPage() {
	const res = await fetch('https://api.example.com/posts')
	const posts = await res.json()

	return (
		<ul>
			{posts.map((post: { id: string; title: string }) => (
				<li key={post.id}>{post.title}</li>
			))}
		</ul>
	)
}
```

This keeps the page static, but allows it to refresh at most once per hour.

You can also set revalidation on an individual fetch:

```tsx
await fetch('https://api.example.com/posts', {
	next: { revalidate: 3600 },
})
```

### ISR For Dynamic Routes

```tsx
// app/blog/[id]/page.tsx
export const revalidate = 3600

export async function generateStaticParams() {
	const posts = await fetch('https://api.example.com/posts').then((res) =>
		res.json(),
	)

	return posts.map((post: { id: string }) => ({
		id: String(post.id),
	}))
}

export default async function Page({
	params,
}: {
	params: Promise<{ id: string }>
}) {
	const { id } = await params

	const post = await fetch(`https://api.example.com/posts/${id}`).then((res) =>
		res.json(),
	)

	return <h1>{post.title}</h1>
}
```

Important: if a route uses `cache: 'no-store'`, or otherwise becomes dynamic,
it is no longer using ISR for that route render.

## 6. On-Demand Revalidation

When data changes, invalidate the cached route or tagged data.

### Revalidate a route

```tsx
// app/actions.ts
'use server'

import { revalidatePath } from 'next/cache'

export async function createPost(formData: FormData) {
	const title = String(formData.get('title') || '')

	await fetch('https://api.example.com/posts', {
		method: 'POST',
		headers: { 'Content-Type': 'application/json' },
		body: JSON.stringify({ title }),
	})

	revalidatePath('/blog')
}
```

### Revalidate tagged data

```tsx
await fetch('https://api.example.com/posts', {
	next: { tags: ['posts'] },
})
```

```tsx
// app/actions.ts
'use server'

import { revalidateTag } from 'next/cache'

export async function refreshPosts() {
	revalidateTag('posts')
}
```

Prefer `revalidatePath()` for most cases. Use `revalidateTag()` when several
pages share the same cached data source.

## 7. Caching Mental Model

The caching guide breaks things down into four layers:

- Request Memoization: dedupes the same work during a single render
- Data Cache: persists fetched data on the server
- Full Route Cache: caches the rendered HTML and RSC payload
- Router Cache: caches RSC payloads in the browser during navigation

The simplest rule is:

- default behavior leans static and cached
- `cache: 'no-store'` makes data request-time fresh
- `revalidate` keeps a route static but refreshable
- `cookies()`, `headers()`, and `searchParams` make a route dynamic

## 8. Forms And Server Actions

Server Actions are the main modern mutation pattern in App Router forms.

```tsx
// app/invoices/page.tsx
export default function Page() {
	async function createInvoice(formData: FormData) {
		'use server'

		const rawFormData = {
			customerId: formData.get('customerId'),
			amount: formData.get('amount'),
			status: formData.get('status'),
		}

		console.log(rawFormData)
	}

	return (
		<form action={createInvoice}>
			<input name="customerId" />
			<input name="amount" />
			<input name="status" />
			<button type="submit">Save</button>
		</form>
	)
}
```

For richer UX, use `useActionState` and `useFormStatus`.

```tsx
'use client'

import { useActionState } from 'react'
import { useFormStatus } from 'react-dom'

function SubmitButton() {
	const { pending } = useFormStatus()

	return (
		<button disabled={pending} type="submit">
			Save
		</button>
	)
}

export function Signup({
	action,
}: {
	action: (
		prevState: { message: string },
		formData: FormData,
	) => Promise<{ message: string }>
}) {
	const [state, formAction] = useActionState(action, { message: '' })

	return (
		<form action={formAction}>
			<input name="email" required type="email" />
			<p aria-live="polite">{state.message}</p>
			<SubmitButton />
		</form>
	)
}
```

## Rules Of Thumb

- Start with a Server Component.
- If the page can be cached, keep it static.
- If it must be fresh every request, use `cache: 'no-store'`.
- If it should stay static but update over time, use ISR with `revalidate`.
- If data changes after a mutation, call `revalidatePath()` or
  `revalidateTag()`.
- Use `loading.tsx` and `Suspense` for streaming.
- Use Server Actions for form submissions and mutations.

